<dl id="n38141b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38141b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38141b"> 141(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ sa = sow ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38141b"><li>FW 130.17 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n38141b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n38141b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38141b">MS BL 47475-232</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:265 <a name="fad6y" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fad6y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad6.htm#n38141b">Draft: I.6&sect;1.6</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The old philologists, such as Franz Bopp and Max M&uuml;ller,]</font> discovered that all the native words of these various <font color="green">[Indo-European]</font> languages could be derived from a relatively small number of <font color="green">[&ldquo;gestural-phonemic&rdquo;]</font> root words, expressive of general concepts &mdash; mostly actions &mdash; such as AD eat, AN breathe, TAN stretch, DA give, RUP break, <mark>SA sow</mark> (corn), SU squeeze out. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPBP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RPBP"><cite title="source">Babel, or The Past, Present and Future of Human Speech</cite></a> (1930) 47</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
